          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "Occurrence of clinical and subclinical infection in a community is responsible for herd immunity. Herd immunity; * It is the level of resistance of a community or group of people to a paicular disease. * Herd immunity provides an immunological barrier to the spread of disease in the human herd. * The epidemic wave declined with a build-up of herd immunity following natural infection. * It is neither possible nor necessary to achieve 100 per cent herd immunity in a population to halt an epidemic or control disease, as seen in SMALL POX eradication. * Herd immunity implies group protection beyond that afforded by the protection of immunized individuals. It provides an immunological barrier to the spread of disease in the human herd. * It may lead to elimination of the disease in due course (Eg. Poliomyelitis and Diphtheria). * In the case of tetanus, however, herd immunity does not protect the individual."
